Those qualities were lost on potential employers conditioned to think otherwise of vets entering the work force.  As Michael L. Lanning pointed out in Vietnam at the Movies, long before the war was over, Hollywood was &quot;already depicting the returning veteran ... as dependent on drugs and alcohol and too incompetent to sustain relationships or employment' &quot;<br>
The 1969-71 recession caused veteran unemployment to soar, prompting the creation of the President's Jobs For Veterans Committee in October 1970.<br>
It is best remembered for the &quot;Don't Forget, Hire the Vet&quot; campaign.  A massive mailing in February 1971, however, drew less than a 2% response from employers.  That March, unemployment among Vietnam-era vets peaked at 402,000-a rate of I 1 % for those ages 20-29 (76% of the era).<br>
The Emergency EmploymentAct of 1971 was passed in response, providing government jobs to 75,000 veterans within two years.  That in turn prompted the women's liberation movement to attack veterans preference.<br>
In 1971, the National Organization for Women (NOW) passed a resolution stat ing: &quot;NOW opposes any state, federal, county, or municipal employment law or program giving special preference to veterans' &quot; This was at a time when women were exempt from military service and 2,348 GIs died serving in Vietnam.<br>
A Supreme Court decision (7-2) of June 5, 1979, upheld the constitutionality of veterans preference.  Assaults on the law, however, intensified.  NOW's resolution has never been rescinded or modified.<br>
A full 28% of vets had difficulties finding jobs, and no doubt stereotyping was a cause.  A fourth of employers surveyed in the 1970s felt military service was unimportant.  &quot;You learned not to put Vietnam on your resum6 because you wouldn't get a job&quot; recalled Wisconsin vet Ted Poull for the 1996 book Voices From Vietnam.<br>
Tony Pirrone, later an oil company executive, stopped listing his vet status on his resume, too.  &quot;During a job interview with an executive at Procter and Gamble, the damn guy wanted to see the needle tracks in my arm!,&quot; he said.  &quot;It was about the time the drug issue was really starting to come out ... I almost decked him.&quot;<br>
Harbison, a rifleman in Vietnam, wrote how in August 1969 in a Massachusetts mill town he was turned down for an unskilled, summer job: &quot;It was as if a young veteran repeatedly had to explain and justify to his friends, fellow students, co-workers and even to his family why and how he served his country.&quot;<br>
As late as 1986, an article in the Harvard Business Review entitled &quot;The Unknown Vietnam Manager&quot; concluded: &quot;Many Vietnam veterans have found it necessary to deny their combat experience in order to secure employment.  The Vietnam experience's positive lessons, including maturity, a sense of purpose and self-confidence have not received much press attention.&quot; That remains unchanged today.<br>

